          "body": "Paul anticipates the obvious Jewish objection: *but the Gentiles never had Sinai*. He answers in vv. 12-16. Gentiles *do not have the Law* (in the formal Mosaic sense) but they *do instinctively the things of the Law* — meaning some Gentiles, in some matters, in some moments, fulfill what the Law commands. How? Because *the work of the Law is written in their hearts* (v. 15), and *their conscience bears witness*. This is general revelation in its ethical dimension, parallel to 1:19-20's general revelation in its cosmological dimension. The Gentile is not condemned for failing to keep a law he never received; he is judged by the light he had. Verse 16 then names the Judge: *Christ Jesus*. The same Jesus who saves in chapter 3 is the Judge in chapter 2. Substitution at the cross and judgment from the throne are not two Christs but one."
